      <chapter xml:id="ch-week-5-8-9-10-possibly-start-12">
        <title>Week 5: 8, 9, 10, possibly start 12</title>

        <p>
          <term>Chapter 9 Learning goals:</term>
        </p>

        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                Be familiar with the properties of determinants (Determinants of special forms, row-operations)
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Be able to compute determinants of larger matrices using properties of determinants
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Instructor Notes:</em> I give a quick proof of many of the determinant properties: multiplying a row by a constant, det(A)=det(AT), having a row of zeros makes det(A)=0. You can likely have them participate and give you ideas on how to prove these. I show that adding a multiple to another row doesn’t change the determinant by showing it for 2x2. It’s also useful to point out at this stage that they should be careful about row operations: 3r1+r2r2 won’t change the determinant, but r1+3r2r2 will change it.
        </p>

        <p>
          <term>Chapter 10 Learning goals:</term>
        </p>

        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              <p>
                Be familiar with the properties of determinants (Determinant of a product)
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Know the relationship between determinants and inverses
              </p>
            </li>

            <li>
              <p>
                Know the equivalent properties to determine if a matrix is invertible (see <url href="https://sites.ualberta.ca/~jsylvest/books/DLA/section-more-det-theory.html#theorem-more-det-equiv-to-invertible">Theorem 10.5.3: Characterizations of Invertibility</url> of your textbook, i.e.
                “Box of Facts”)-We will add to this
              </p>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
          <em>Instructor Notes:</em> We’re going to skip the adjoint formula and Cramer’s rule for homework and testing. You are welcome to mention it in class, but don’t spend much time on it. It’s likely that this section will take less than 50 minutes, so try to start Chapter 12 this week if possible.
        </p>

        <p>
          A way to justify that det(A)=0 iff A is singular that doesn’t need elementary matrices: Reduce A to its reduced echelon form, B.
          If it’s the identity, then since det(I) is not zero, A’s determinant is not zero.
          If it has a row of zeros, then det(B)=0, which means A’s determinant is also zero.
        </p>

        <p>
          Again, spend some time discussing the Characterizations of invertibility with your students.
          Ask them which implications are not clear to them at this point, and spend a few minutes discussing them.
          Also play around with rephrasing the false version of these statements.
          For example, if a matrix is not invertible, why must its rank not be equal to its size?
        </p>
      </chapter>


